00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:09.180
The analytical part
will delve into the lack

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:13.950
of shared prosperity we see
in the American economy.

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:17.400
Once upon a time in America,
the prosperity we generated

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:19.470
was shared pretty broadly
so that rich Americans,

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.690
middle class Americans,
poor Americans

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:24.030
we either thrived together,
or we struggle together.

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:26.880
And since all boats either
rose or fell with the tide,

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:28.770
the challenge was
fairly straightforward.

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:30.186
How do we keep the
tide coming in?

00:03:30.186 --> 00:03:31.320
All right?

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:34.980
But that is not what we see
in the American economy today.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:39.500
Instead, what I think we see is
an economy doing half its job

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.850
where big companies and the
people who work for them

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:44.900
and invest in them
are doing pretty well.

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:46.770
But working class,
middle class Americans

00:03:46.770 --> 00:03:49.870
are struggling, as are
many small businesses.

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:52.050
And I've become convinced
this is the number one

00:03:52.050 --> 00:03:54.690
economic, social, and
increasingly political problem

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:55.490
in our country.

00:03:55.490 --> 00:03:57.810
That many of the things that
might concern many of us--

00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:01.170
the rise of populism, even the
financial crisis of the last

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:02.820
decade--

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:04.860
are as much causes of
that lack of shared

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:08.410
prosperity as independent
events in and of themselves.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:14.340
And I want to share with you
some fairly sobering symptoms,

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:16.890
as well as offer a
diagnosis before I

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:18.190
move to the prescription.

00:04:18.190 --> 00:04:20.430
Now, with the prescription,
that brings me

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:21.740
to the call to action.

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:23.190
And the call to
action is embodied

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.770
in the title of the
talk, "Will We Restore

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:27.510
Shared Prosperity in America?"

00:04:27.510 --> 00:04:29.190
I chose the title
very deliberately.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:30.630
It's not can we.

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:32.190
Sometimes, you read
stuff out there

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:35.280
that makes it feel like
the economic outcomes will

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:40.560
be dictated by inexorable
forces of global change

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:43.030
or technological change.

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:45.770
I actually believe those forces
are extraordinarily important.

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:47.270
But I also believe
what we have here

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:49.530
is essentially a social choice.

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:51.510
We get to decide.

00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:54.174
And I want to take
the talk personally.

00:04:54.174 --> 00:04:55.590
I believe that
people with Google,

00:04:55.590 --> 00:04:58.380
individually and
collectively, can actually

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:01.620
help to shape and make
that social decision.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:05.810
It will require, I believe, an
approach, an approach that's

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:07.550
not discussed as
much as it should be,

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:10.820
an approach that I'll try
to highlight and illustrate

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:13.340
when I move to the
prescription, an approach

00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:15.950
that I actually see
already implicit in some

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:19.230
of the social and philanthropic
efforts of the company,

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:21.920
but an approach that I think
is actually made more powerful

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:23.600
if we make it explicit.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:25.310
So that's where I'm heading.

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:28.970
I want to start with the
symptoms and just some facts

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:31.910
about prosperity
in America today.

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:34.340
I'm going to start
with the good news.

00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:37.980
I will warn you the good news
is not going to last very long.

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:40.140
And this could be a bit
of a roller coaster ride.

00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:43.850
I promise everyone you
cannot leave without an equal

00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:47.230
and opposite offsetting
dose of optimism by the end.

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:47.990
OK?

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:50.420
But bear with me through
some of the sobering stuff.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.760
The good news first, though.

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:55.100
Total prosperity in
America-- turns out

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:58.400
we're generating lots of
prosperity in the country.

00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:00.800
One indicator of this is
gross domestic product.

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:04.210
Here we've got
real GDP in America

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:09.650
over time indexed back to 1995
shown versus Europe and Japan.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:12.140
And the good news is that,
in fact, the American economy

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:15.890
powered into and powered out
of the great recession stronger

00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:17.870
than the other advanced
economies of the world.

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:19.536
Now, it turns out the
growth rates here,

00:06:19.536 --> 00:06:21.380
they are lower than
we saw in the years

00:06:21.380 --> 00:06:22.970
immediately after World War II.

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:24.200
They're relatively low.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:28.190
But the total pie, the total
pie is growing pretty well.

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:31.580
Now, part of that pie shows
up as corporate profit.

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:32.967
This looks like good news too.

00:06:32.967 --> 00:06:35.300
So it turns up, when you only
looks at corporate profit,

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:39.650
either as a portion of GDP,
in red and on the right,

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:43.120
or in total real dollars,
in blue and on the left.

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:45.940
Corporate profits are close
to all-time record highs.

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:49.040
OK, so the corporate part of
the pie is just doing fine.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:51.530
Now, I want to turn
what's happening outside

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:52.850
of the corporate sector.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:56.270
And I'm going to start by
focusing on income, right,

00:06:56.270 --> 00:06:59.430
a key indicator of prosperity,
and income distribution

00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:02.085
and actually look at income
from like four different angles.

00:07:02.085 --> 00:07:03.710
So you can see
different aspects of it.

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:04.889
You can get it totaled up.

00:07:04.889 --> 00:07:06.680
And I'll also look at
two things that drive

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:10.400
it-- job growth and startups.

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:12.500
With income, I want to
start with, I think,

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:15.590
a tremendously interesting
and sobering analysis

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:17.660
that some colleagues at
Berkeley and in France

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:19.670
did very recently.

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:21.630
They took the
income distribution.

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:24.060
They looked at individuals
in each percentile.

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:24.800
OK?

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:28.850
And they asked, over the
first half and the second half

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:31.520
of the post-war
period, how did income

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:34.340
grow for individuals in each
percentile of the income

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:35.610
distribution.

00:07:35.610 --> 00:07:38.210
So this is the first half
of the post-war period,

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:40.230
1946 through 1980.

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:43.229
And this is different points
in the income distribution.

00:07:43.229 --> 00:07:45.020
And first of all, the
good news is the line

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:46.310
as a whole is pretty high.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:47.420
That's terrific.

00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:49.670
And in fact, the
poorest Americans

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:53.360
saw the greatest percentage
gains in real income.

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:56.660
And the richest Americans saw
modest gains, but still gains,

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:58.190
but lower gains.

00:07:58.190 --> 00:07:59.930
Now, we move forward
to the second half

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:04.910
of the post-war period,
1980 through 2014.

00:08:04.910 --> 00:08:07.960
And the line rotates
dramatically.

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:08.655
OK?

00:08:08.655 --> 00:08:11.972
All right, I mean your gasp is
exactly my reaction as well.

00:08:11.972 --> 00:08:12.930
So what do we see here?

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:16.430
We see the poorest Americans,
basically, barely keeping up.

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:19.970
We see the very, very,
very wealthiest Americans

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:22.580
seeing unprecedented
gains in income over time.

00:08:22.580 --> 00:08:23.810
All right?

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:26.040
So there you get the
whole distribution.

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:28.250
Let's now zero in on
one particular point.

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:30.890
Let's zero in on the median and
look at the median over time.

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:32.265
Because if we had
a world-- if we

00:08:32.265 --> 00:08:34.370
had a country of
shared prosperity,

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:36.890
we'd expect to see median
household income in real terms,

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:39.799
in inflation-adjusted
terms, going up over time.

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:40.520
All right?

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.440
We might see ups and
downs around recessions,

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:44.210
but, generally, an upward trend.

00:08:44.210 --> 00:08:47.360
If you look back far enough
at median household income,

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:50.210
that's actually what we saw,
all right, from 1975 here

00:08:50.210 --> 00:08:51.859
to around the year 2000.

00:08:51.859 --> 00:08:53.900
Yeah, there's ups and
downs around the recession,

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:56.990
but basically an upward trend.

00:08:56.990 --> 00:08:59.870
But then things peak in 1999.

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:02.150
We see stagnation, decline.

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:05.010
We do see some gains
in recent years.

00:09:05.010 --> 00:09:07.700
And in fact, the data that
were released two weeks ago

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:09.260
showed that real
median household

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:12.990
income exceeded the 1999
peak for the first time.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:15.710
People celebrated, and
we should celebrate.

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:18.440
We should also keep in mind
exactly what we're celebrating.

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:20.150
We're celebrating
that we are back

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:22.600
to where we were 17 years ago.

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:23.930
OK?

00:09:23.930 --> 00:09:25.942
This is not just
true at the median.

00:09:25.942 --> 00:09:28.400
It's true all the way down to
the very bottom of the income

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:28.941
distribution.

00:09:28.941 --> 00:09:33.170
And it goes up to around
the 95th or above percentile

00:09:33.170 --> 00:09:36.770
that since 1999 we've seen
essentially stagnation, decline

00:09:36.770 --> 00:09:38.870
and then recovery.

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:42.465
So that's deeply sobering.

00:09:42.465 --> 00:09:45.920
Another thing is just looking
at how it spread geographically.

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:51.260
So let's now zero in on 15
years from 1999 to 2014.

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:53.900
and look at the change in
real median household income.

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:57.110
But now, let's do it
by county in the US.

00:09:57.110 --> 00:09:59.270
And what you see
here is declines

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:02.420
in real median household income
in the reds, the oranges,

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:04.700
the shades of
yellow and increases

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:07.680
in the blues and the whites.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:11.790
And you can see deep declines
in the Midwest, deep declines

00:10:11.790 --> 00:10:16.020
in the South, the Northeast and
the Rockies not quite as bad.

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:18.390
You actually see gains in
a big chunk of the country

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:20.900
where there are very few people.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:22.650
And you can almost
make-- you can actually

00:10:22.650 --> 00:10:27.270
make out the oil shale fields
in North Dakota and west Texas.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:27.930
Right?

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:31.080
If you squint very hard,
you squint very hard,

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:34.860
you can see some highly
populous but prosperous pockets

00:10:34.860 --> 00:10:35.775
on the coasts.

00:10:35.775 --> 00:10:37.440
So you can see Boston.

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:39.570
You can see the Bay Area.

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:41.630
You can see Washington DC.

00:10:41.630 --> 00:10:42.960
You can see LA.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:46.690
But both in terms of the gains
across the income distribution

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:51.630
and also gains across the
country, really uneven outcomes

00:10:51.630 --> 00:10:53.370
on median household income.

00:10:53.370 --> 00:10:54.780
All right?

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:58.460
The last angle on income
I want to give you

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:00.930
is something that
colleagues in the Econ

00:11:00.930 --> 00:11:04.140
Department at Harvard and
Stanford have shown recently.

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:05.760
They did a very clever analysis.

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:10.590
They basically ask first
what is the American dream.

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:13.350
And they realized that at
least one key component of it

00:11:13.350 --> 00:11:16.320
is my kids are
better off than I am,

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:18.630
and I'm better off
than my parents.

00:11:18.630 --> 00:11:21.090
So they took tax records,
looked at income,

00:11:21.090 --> 00:11:24.390
and linked together
parents and kids.

00:11:24.390 --> 00:11:26.920
And they can look at people
in different birth cohorts

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:31.260
and ask, for instance,
for someone born in 1940,

00:11:31.260 --> 00:11:35.160
when they were age 30 in
1970, are they better off

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:37.170
than their parents were
when their parents were

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:38.595
30 years old.

00:11:38.595 --> 00:11:43.530
It turns out for someone born in
1940, the answer was about 90%

00:11:43.530 --> 00:11:45.820
of them were better off than
their parents at age 30.

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:46.650
OK?

00:11:46.650 --> 00:11:50.780
But you can see, you know,
the decline in this figure.

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:53.820
All the way to, you
know, those born in 1984,

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:56.465
who turned 30 in 2014 when the
data set ends, it turns out

00:11:56.465 --> 00:11:58.590
only half of them are better
off than their parents

00:11:58.590 --> 00:11:59.780
were at age 30.

00:11:59.780 --> 00:12:02.760
So it's gone from being a
kind of 90%, almost a sure

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:06.310
bet, to being a coin toss.

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:07.720
Now, I promised sobering data.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:08.220
Right?

00:12:08.220 --> 00:12:09.480
So are we sobered so far?

