I want to look at two
underlying drivers of income

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:16.530
and prosperity and
shared prosperity.

00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:18.540
One is job creation.

00:12:18.540 --> 00:12:20.370
Another is startups.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:23.430
So in job creation, I
want to take a quick look

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:25.180
at the great American
job machine, right,

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:27.710
which clearly is a driver
of shared prosperity.

00:12:27.710 --> 00:12:29.590
And here's one
way to look at it.

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:32.570
It's the rolling 10-year
compounded annual growth

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:34.320
rate and the number
of private-sector jobs

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:35.680
in the country.

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:38.700
So the number for 1985 was 2.7%.

00:12:38.700 --> 00:12:41.310
That means in the
decade before 1985,

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:45.120
the economy produced new jobs at
an average annual clip of 2.7%.

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:46.170
All right?

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:48.430
And you can see that,
for a long period,

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:50.460
the great American
job machine could

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:52.770
be counted upon in
any given decade

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:55.269
to produce new jobs at
about 2% clip per year.

00:12:55.269 --> 00:12:57.060
There'd be ups and
downs within the decade.

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:58.170
But give me a decade.

00:12:58.170 --> 00:13:00.360
I can give you 2% annual growth.

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:04.200
And then somewhere around
2000, something happens.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:06.195
The job machine
starts to sputter.

00:13:06.195 --> 00:13:07.050
All right?

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:10.120
And we drop to historically
low rates of job growth,

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:12.600
which for working and
middle class Americans

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:16.099
is a deeply distressing outcome.

00:13:16.099 --> 00:13:18.140
I also want to turn,
particularly for this crowd,

00:13:18.140 --> 00:13:19.700
I thought turn to startups.

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:20.489
All right?

00:13:20.489 --> 00:13:22.530
I think most of us have
the impression, certainly

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:24.960
on campus where I live,
it seems like it's

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:26.310
the golden age of startups.

00:13:26.310 --> 00:13:28.710
Like if you're at HBS as
an MBA, and you're not

00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:31.094
involved in two startups,
people will wonder what

00:13:31.094 --> 00:13:32.260
you're doing with your time.

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:33.810
Right?

00:13:33.810 --> 00:13:36.240
And I think-- when you think
about it, barriers to entry

00:13:36.240 --> 00:13:37.050
have fallen.

00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.840
We can now outsource production.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.700
We can market via Google.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.137
We can deliver via UPS.

00:13:43.137 --> 00:13:44.970
Seems like barriers to
entry have come down.

00:13:44.970 --> 00:13:49.620
It turns out that impression
is true inside a particularly

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:50.810
small bubble.

00:13:50.810 --> 00:13:53.400
And if you actually
look at the startups

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:58.350
as a portion of all US firms,
it's been in steady decline

00:13:58.350 --> 00:14:00.697
since the late 1970s.

00:14:00.697 --> 00:14:02.280
On Tuesday of this
week, they actually

00:14:02.280 --> 00:14:03.990
released the 2015 data.

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:06.780
It's up a tiny little
bit, a tenth of a point.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:09.660
Now, just to remind
you, again, it's

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:11.550
not that we're not
producing prosperity.

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:13.550
It's that we're not
producing shared prosperity.

00:14:13.550 --> 00:14:15.930
And just to reinforce
that, here's

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:18.660
a chart where we
look at two things--

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:21.330
blue and on the left,
the average income

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:24.480
in real dollars among
those in the bottom 99%

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:26.580
of the population over a
very long period of time,

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:29.070
going back basically to
when we started doing income

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:34.050
taxes in America in 1913, and
then, in red and on the right,

00:14:34.050 --> 00:14:36.000
what happens for
those in the top 1%.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.920
So you can see very clearly,
from about the end of World War

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:41.600
II through the mid-1970s,
this is essentially

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:44.010
the golden age of the
American middle class

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:47.650
and then, from the mid-1980s
until very recently,

00:14:47.650 --> 00:14:51.060
maybe even today, the
golden age of the 1%.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:53.010
So we've got a
situation where we

00:14:53.010 --> 00:14:56.100
see a true, deep lack of shared
prosperity in the country.

00:14:56.100 --> 00:15:00.510
And I'm sorry to show you the
baby from different angles.

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:04.620
But the baby is ugly from
each direction, I'm afraid.

00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:05.940
What's going on?

00:15:05.940 --> 00:15:08.700
We need to move from just the
symptoms to the diagnosis.

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:12.620
I want to offer a basic
narrative that I think captures

00:15:12.620 --> 00:15:14.019
a lot of what's going on.

00:15:14.019 --> 00:15:15.560
It's not going to
capture everything.

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:16.190
All right?

00:15:16.190 --> 00:15:18.200
But I think it'll
capture the basics.

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:20.515
It starts with an idea.

00:15:20.515 --> 00:15:23.992
And it's an idea that my
colleagues Gary Pisano

00:15:23.992 --> 00:15:26.450
and Willy Shih have really made
central in my own thinking.

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:28.670
It's the idea of the commons--

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:32.450
that there are certain shared
resources that every citizen,

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:35.360
every community, every
company relies upon

00:15:35.360 --> 00:15:38.030
in order to be productive
and prosperous.

00:15:38.030 --> 00:15:41.330
Every community needs
a educated populace,

00:15:41.330 --> 00:15:45.380
needs a skilled workforce,
needs a strong infrastructure,

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:48.080
some basic R&amp;D. All Right

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:50.930
And the truly amazing thing
about the United States,

00:15:50.930 --> 00:15:55.670
historically, is that
locally invested companies

00:15:55.670 --> 00:16:00.240
and a functioning government at
the federal and the local level

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:02.450
managed to invest
deeply and build

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:05.240
the most productive commons
the world had ever seen.

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:06.500
In fact, we not only built
a productive commons.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:07.624
We were innovators in this.

00:16:07.624 --> 00:16:09.500
From the
transcontinental railroad

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:14.060
to the interstate highway system
from universal public education

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:17.540
in the 1840s to the GI
Bill after World War II,

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:20.090
we innovated it and
built the commons.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:22.320
Now, I do want to
be very, very clear.

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:23.810
This was not good for everyone.

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:25.265
Like the good old days was not--

00:16:25.265 --> 00:16:28.940
they just weren't so good across
big portions of population.

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:30.770
The interstate
highway system cut

00:16:30.770 --> 00:16:34.040
through the heart of many
African-American neighborhoods.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:38.240
The GI Bill was not shared
equally across the population,

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:39.500
either racially--

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:42.530
very few women benefited from
the GI Bill, for instance.

00:16:42.530 --> 00:16:44.810
But for a big chunk
of the population,

00:16:44.810 --> 00:16:47.090
we built a strong commons.

00:16:47.090 --> 00:16:48.710
Then what happens?

00:16:48.710 --> 00:16:52.130
We hit around 1980,
and we see changes

00:16:52.130 --> 00:16:54.380
in geopolitics,
changes in technology,

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:56.720
changes in governance.

00:16:56.720 --> 00:16:59.520
Suddenly, we create
automation and globalization.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:01.160
It becomes possible
to do business

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:02.870
from anywhere to anywhere.

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:04.400
And we start to get
new technologies

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:05.375
for automating jobs.

00:17:05.375 --> 00:17:06.619
All right?

00:17:06.619 --> 00:17:08.957
And this had tremendous
benefits for the US economy.

00:17:08.957 --> 00:17:09.790
Let's be very clear.

00:17:09.790 --> 00:17:11.300
This was beneficial.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:14.270
But it also tended to weaken the
connections between companies

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:16.250
and their communities,
the connections that

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:20.480
had made companies eager to
invest in the local commons.

00:17:20.480 --> 00:17:22.160
If I am born in a
small city, and I

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:26.010
know that I'm going to be
starting my business, growing

00:17:26.010 --> 00:17:29.397
my business, and, you
know, living in a community

00:17:29.397 --> 00:17:31.980
where I've got to rely upon the
local public education system,

00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:33.855
I've got really strong
incentive to make sure

00:17:33.855 --> 00:17:35.900
that school system
operates well.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:39.080
So but we've got now a situation
where there's globalization

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:40.260
and additional automation.

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:43.910
So maybe I can replace
individuals with machinery.

00:17:43.910 --> 00:17:46.700
So the incentives to invest in
the commons among businesses

00:17:46.700 --> 00:17:48.410
deteriorates.

00:17:48.410 --> 00:17:50.600
This, of course,
puts intense pressure

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:52.430
on the middle class
in our society.

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:53.120
Right?

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:55.520
Middle class, working
class, finds itself

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:59.570
in intense competition for
jobs with hundreds of millions

00:17:59.570 --> 00:18:03.470
of ambitious, skilled
workers around the world,

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:07.400
and also, implicitly, competing
for jobs against technology

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:10.700
that's improving at the
rate of Moore's law.

00:18:10.700 --> 00:18:13.700
On the other hand, on the other
end of the skills distribution,

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.280
if you happen to have unique
skills that you can market

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:18.740
globally and can be
leveraged by technology,

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:20.060
this is a great moment.

00:18:20.060 --> 00:18:20.870
Right?

00:18:20.870 --> 00:18:26.090
So income inequality starts
to rise at this point.

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:29.360
Then the next question becomes
how did we, as a society,

00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:32.100
respond to pressure
in the middle class.

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:33.800
We could have doubled
down, I think,

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:37.160
on making the middle
class so, you know,

00:18:37.160 --> 00:18:39.260
so educated, so
skilled, so supported

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:42.080
by strong infrastructure and
other parts of the commons

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:44.840
that it can compete with anyone,
anywhere around the world.

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:46.190
All right?

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:49.380
Instead, what we honestly did--

00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:50.630
and let me be clear.

00:18:50.630 --> 00:18:53.210
I don't want to pin this on
one political party or another.

00:18:53.210 --> 00:18:56.540
I think there's enough blame
here to go around, actually.

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:58.310
I think what we
did, as a society,

00:18:58.310 --> 00:19:01.070
is we made a series of
unsustainable promises

00:19:01.070 --> 00:19:03.350
to maintain the illusion
of shared prosperity,

00:19:03.350 --> 00:19:07.070
even as things started
to deteriorate.

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:11.600
They're promises like
please, middle class,

00:19:11.600 --> 00:19:13.910
don't worry about your
stagnant household income.

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:16.260
We will extend
additional credit to you.

00:19:16.260 --> 00:19:19.100
Please go out and
buy more stuff.

00:19:19.100 --> 00:19:21.260
Particularly, buy houses.

00:19:21.260 --> 00:19:21.920
Right?

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:23.930
So after the dot.com
bubble bursts,

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:28.640
we keep interest rates low,
encouraging house buying.

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:31.010
And we build a
bubble, which we come

00:19:31.010 --> 00:19:33.383
to live with during
the financial crisis.

00:19:33.383 --> 00:19:37.670
Promises like the
government will directly

00:19:37.670 --> 00:19:40.640
cover your health care
costs during your retirement

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:44.960
and promises like we'll do
all of this while lowering

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:47.150
tax rates in every tax bracket.

00:19:47.150 --> 00:19:48.090
Right?

00:19:48.090 --> 00:19:49.740
You take those promises.

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:53.900
You couple them with two
wars and a nasty recession.

00:19:53.900 --> 00:19:55.340
And you wind up
with a government,

00:19:55.340 --> 00:19:58.280
which is both financially
hobbled and politically

00:19:58.280 --> 00:19:59.420
divided.

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:01.130
And where do the cuts come?

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:03.920
Basically, they come in
investments in the comments.

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:04.640
Right?

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:08.000
So you wind up with footloose
firms and a hobbled government.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.620
And who's making the
investments in infrastructure,

00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:14.560
to individuals and
innovation, and so forth?

00:20:14.560 --> 00:20:16.560
Unfortunately, not
enough anywhere.

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:17.360
Right?

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:21.750
Now, one particular
look at this issue

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:24.420
comes from surveys we've done,
as part of the Competitiveness

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:25.680
Project, of our alumni.

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:28.110
So we're fortunate to
have tens of thousands

00:20:28.110 --> 00:20:32.130
of alums around the
world who will generously

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:34.050
share their perspective
from the front lines

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:35.580
of global capitalism.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:38.010
Among the things that
we've asked them,

00:20:38.010 --> 00:20:41.100
we've asked them to look
at a bunch of elements

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:43.471
of the business
environment in America,

00:20:43.471 --> 00:20:44.970
which prior research
has shown to be

00:20:44.970 --> 00:20:47.970
drivers of competitiveness and
drivers of shared prosperity.

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:50.860
And for about each of these, we
asked them two basic questions.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:53.704
The first question was
how's the US doing compared

00:20:53.704 --> 00:20:54.870
to other advanced economies.

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:57.209
That will become
my horizontal axis.

00:20:57.209 --> 00:20:59.250
And then we've asked what's
America's trajectory.

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:00.999
Are we getting better
or staying the same,

00:21:00.999 --> 00:21:02.920
getting worse in
each one of these?

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:04.870
And that will be
the vertical axis.

00:21:04.870 --> 00:21:06.977
Now, the great news
about the US is,

00:21:06.977 --> 00:21:08.810
in fact, we've got some
great strengths that

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:09.870
are getting even better.

00:21:09.870 --> 00:21:11.660
We've got a great
context for innovation.

00:21:11.660 --> 00:21:13.110
We've got vibrant
capital markets.

00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:16.050
We've got high-quality
firm management.

00:21:16.050 --> 00:21:18.142
We've got great
research universities.

00:21:18.142 --> 00:21:20.100
The problem is those
strengths are weighed down

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:22.380
by other strengths that
are getting worse--

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:25.290
our pools of skilled labor,
our macroeconomic policy,

00:21:25.290 --> 00:21:28.290
for instance, our
regulatory system--

00:21:28.290 --> 00:21:30.240
and by weaknesses
that are getting worse

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:31.980
in the eyes of our alums--

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:35.250
a convoluted tax code, a
paralyzed political system

00:21:35.250 --> 00:21:38.080
at the national level, a
costly healthcare system,

00:21:38.080 --> 00:21:41.650
a very patchy, uneven K
through 12 education system,

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:45.210
and logistics and infrastructure
with significant weaknesses.

00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:47.040
Now, if you stare
at that chart, you

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:50.460
can essentially see, with
a little bit of squinting,

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:52.410
the underlying drivers
of the lack of shared

00:21:52.410 --> 00:21:53.520
prosperity in the country.

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:54.478
Because think about it.

00:21:54.478 --> 00:21:57.330
If you're a large corporation,
running a large corporation,

00:21:57.330 --> 00:21:59.670
what do you need to do well?

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:01.590
You need access to innovation.

00:22:01.590 --> 00:22:03.390
You need great
research universities.

00:22:03.390 --> 00:22:05.010
You need great capital markets.

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:07.230
You need great firm management.

00:22:07.230 --> 00:22:10.230
And frankly, if you don't
like the national environment,

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:11.680
you are one--

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:14.280
you're like one tax
code, one inversion,

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:18.000
away from getting away from the
convoluted tax code in the US.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.100
You can source talent
from around the world.

00:22:21.100 --> 00:22:26.609
So the K through 12 system is
not a barrier to your progress.

00:22:26.609 --> 00:22:28.650
On the other hand, if you
are a working or middle

00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:33.750
class American, you bring
to work your education,

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.510
your workforce skills.

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:40.200
And you can't escape
the consequences

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:41.760
of the national
political system.

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:44.490
You can't escape the
consequences of the healthcare

00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:46.090
system.

00:22:46.090 --> 00:22:48.810
So essentially, what
you've got is large firms

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:50.880
that can tap the
strengths of the economy

00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:54.870
and can escape the weaknesses
and many, many citizens

00:22:54.870 --> 00:22:56.520
who are reliant
upon the weaknesses

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:59.640
and can't escape
from those weaknesses

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:03.270
as well and very rarely
actually tap into the strengths.

00:23:03.270 --> 00:23:06.030
So that diagnosis,
it acknowledges

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:07.890
things that are kind
of inexorable forces

00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:10.320
like globalization and
technological change.

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:11.880
But it also says look.

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:14.250
We have here a
self-inflicted wound.

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:18.420
The self-inflicted wound is
systematic under-investment

00:23:18.420 --> 00:23:21.660
in the commons on which
many, many Americans depend.

00:23:21.660 --> 00:23:24.840
And the question becomes how
might we fix that problem.

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:26.490
And this leads to
the prescription

00:23:26.490 --> 00:23:29.100
and, ultimately, to
the call to action.

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:31.140
On the prescription
side, let me lay out,

00:23:31.140 --> 00:23:35.460
with a little bit caricature,
what I hear as the major ways

00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:38.910
people talk about restoring
shared prosperity in America.

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:41.670
There are folks who
will basically--

00:23:41.670 --> 00:23:44.970
and I will confess I think
there are largely politicians--

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:48.590
who will essentially say
my plan is to reverse time.

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:49.260
OK?

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:53.730
I'm going to stop globalization
by putting up barriers.

00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:55.380
And we're going
to tax the robots.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:58.890
And we're going to basically--
don't worry about automation.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:00.690
You could probably
hold back the tide

00:24:00.690 --> 00:24:02.490
a little bit there
for a little bit.

00:24:02.490 --> 00:24:05.320
But I think if America
resists the future,

00:24:05.320 --> 00:24:07.260
while the rest of the
world embraces it,

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:10.689
the country will not wind up in
a good place in the long run.

00:24:10.689 --> 00:24:12.480
Second you hear lots
of talks about efforts

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:15.220
to redistribute
income, to redistribute

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:18.450
the gains very directly
and more progressive tax

00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:23.880
code, higher minimum wages, at
the extreme, universal basic

00:24:23.880 --> 00:24:24.750
income.

00:24:24.750 --> 00:24:26.212
Right?

00:24:26.212 --> 00:24:27.670
Once you start
talking about these,

00:24:27.670 --> 00:24:30.700
one's politics quickly
come out to the front.

00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:31.890
I'll confess mine.

00:24:31.890 --> 00:24:34.306
I think we need to talk about
these things very seriously.

00:24:34.306 --> 00:24:38.400
All right, I also live
enough in the real world

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:41.160
to realize that, legislatively,
these things are not

00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:42.429
likely to happen.

00:24:42.429 --> 00:24:44.220
All right, so we have
to find other things.

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:47.130
If we're serious about
restoring shared prosperity,

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:49.800
we, individually, in our
own wish, may work on those,

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:52.390
but we have to work on
other things as well.

00:24:52.390 --> 00:24:54.180
The third category
I'd say is efforts

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:55.962
to boost overall growth rates.

00:24:55.962 --> 00:24:58.170
There are people who say,
look, what we really need--

00:24:58.170 --> 00:25:00.270
let's just boost overall growth.

00:25:00.270 --> 00:25:02.340
And then the boats will
rise with the tide.

00:25:02.340 --> 00:25:05.790
If you really believe that
prosperity in aggregate

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:08.744
will automatically bring shared
prosperity in the country,

00:25:08.744 --> 00:25:10.410
you've kind of not
been paying attention

00:25:10.410 --> 00:25:12.510
for the past couple of decades.

00:25:12.510 --> 00:25:15.570
And then, finally, and where
I find the greatest hope is

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:17.010
efforts to restore the commons.

00:25:17.010 --> 00:25:19.140
And these are region
by region efforts.

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:20.760
They are local efforts.

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:22.290
And they are cross-sector.

00:25:22.290 --> 00:25:23.880
They involve business.

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:27.480
Almost all the time, they
never involve only business.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:28.870
And they are highly innovative.

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:30.390
And I'll just lay
out a few examples

00:25:30.390 --> 00:25:32.010
to give you a taste,
a concrete taste,

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:33.970
of what I'm talking about.

00:25:33.970 --> 00:25:36.120
So one of my favorite
ones involves

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:37.320
a company called Southwire.

00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:41.401
South is a multibillion dollar
maker of cable and wire.

00:25:41.401 --> 00:25:43.650
There's a one in five chance
their product is actually

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:47.470
in your wall at home or my
wall, but we don't know it.

00:25:47.470 --> 00:25:49.110
Right?

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:52.650
The Chief Executive of Southwire
realized he had a problem.

00:25:52.650 --> 00:25:56.430
He committed to hire only
high school Graduates

00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:58.560
And in rural Carroll
County, Georgia,

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:01.230
where the company
is based, there just

00:26:01.230 --> 00:26:03.780
weren't enough people
graduating from high school.

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:08.310
So he and his team partnered
with the local school district

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:10.680
and said to the
school district bring

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:14.445
us the most at-risk
students in your system,

00:26:14.445 --> 00:26:16.530
OK, like the people
you are confident

00:26:16.530 --> 00:26:18.210
are going to drop out.

00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:21.840
And we will build a dedicated
factory, staffed entirely

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:25.980
by at-risk high school
students, managed by teachers

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:28.290
and by Southwire managers.

00:26:28.290 --> 00:26:32.220
And the students, if they
go to school in the morning,

00:26:32.220 --> 00:26:34.440
can then work a
four-hour shift for pay

00:26:34.440 --> 00:26:38.380
at Southwire in this dedicated
factory in the afternoon.

00:26:38.380 --> 00:26:40.947
So it turns out this
leads the graduation

00:26:40.947 --> 00:26:43.530
rate for these at-risk students
to go flying through the roof.

00:26:43.530 --> 00:26:46.020
It's above the system average.

00:26:46.020 --> 00:26:48.660
The graduation rate
among at-risk students

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:52.740
who are in the county, but
not in this program, even that

00:26:52.740 --> 00:26:54.990
goes up because of peer effects.

00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:56.580
The managers at
Southwire who are

00:26:56.580 --> 00:26:58.290
doing this adore doing this.

00:26:58.290 --> 00:27:00.360
It gives extra
meaning to their work.

00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:02.100
The school system is delighted.

00:27:02.100 --> 00:27:04.060
And then here's
the kicker for me.

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:07.320
It turns out that a
well-managed, well-trained high

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:11.440
school student is about 35%
more productive than a grownup.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:16.410
So the factory, the
factory that they

00:27:16.410 --> 00:27:18.120
hoped might one day
break even, actually

00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:21.870
starts to print money in month
three, money they then reinvest

00:27:21.870 --> 00:27:23.180
in growing the program.

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:24.670
So that's just one example.

00:27:24.670 --> 00:27:26.090
You can see cross-sector.

00:27:26.090 --> 00:27:27.170
It involves business.

00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:28.260
It involves educators.

00:27:28.260 --> 00:27:30.990
It involves the local
government to some extent.

00:27:30.990 --> 00:27:33.090
And it makes a difference
to building the commons

00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:34.710
in that community.

00:27:34.710 --> 00:27:36.890
Siemens, you know,
global multinational,

00:27:36.890 --> 00:27:38.910
they're energy
equipment business

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:40.595
is based in Charlotte,
North Carolina.

00:27:40.595 --> 00:27:41.970
They realized they
had a problem.

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.130
Their problem was
they could not find

00:27:44.130 --> 00:27:48.300
enough advanced manufacturing
workers in the local workforce.

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:51.090
So you know, Siemens
can go anywhere.

00:27:51.090 --> 00:27:53.250
But instead, they say
they're going to double down

00:27:53.250 --> 00:27:54.070
in North Carolina.

00:27:54.070 --> 00:27:56.790
They partner with Central
Piedmont Community College,

00:27:56.790 --> 00:27:59.100
essentially, to train
the workers they

00:27:59.100 --> 00:28:00.780
would love to hire.

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:03.270
All right, so this means
a deep partnership.

00:28:03.270 --> 00:28:09.220
It means helping to reform the
curriculum in the community

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:09.720
college.

00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:10.970
It means donating equipment.

00:28:10.970 --> 00:28:12.880
It means donating software.

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:14.880
It means a change for the
community college too.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:16.270
They've got to take
their instructors,

00:28:16.270 --> 00:28:18.810
change the curriculum, send
them to Germany to understand

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:21.030
the apprenticeship in
Germany, the apprenticeship

00:28:21.030 --> 00:28:22.500
system in Germany.

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:25.680
But the consequence is a
highly skilled workforce,

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:28.590
which is useful not only
for Siemens, but also

00:28:28.590 --> 00:28:33.610
for other advanced
manufacturers in the community.

00:28:33.610 --> 00:28:37.809
So once again, multi-sector,
local in its character

00:28:37.809 --> 00:28:39.600
and, also, in this case
and in other cases,

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:41.610
involving young leaders.

00:28:41.610 --> 00:28:43.861
I may come back to the Itasca
Project if we have time.

00:28:43.861 --> 00:28:45.485
But the Young American
Leaders Project,

00:28:45.485 --> 00:28:46.830
this is my personal favorite.

00:28:46.830 --> 00:28:48.710
I've been deeply
involved in this one.

00:28:48.710 --> 00:28:51.390
One thing we realized at
Harvard Business School, as we

00:28:51.390 --> 00:28:54.690
collected scores upon
scores of examples

00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:57.672
like this of local cross-sector
collaborations that

00:28:57.672 --> 00:28:59.130
were rebuilding
the commons, making

00:28:59.130 --> 00:29:02.490
a difference in the individual
communities, what we realized

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:03.840
is the ideas weren't spreading.

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:05.860
They were bottled up
in local communities.

00:29:05.860 --> 00:29:08.310
We'd go to Nashville
and talk about what

00:29:08.310 --> 00:29:11.620
we'd seen in Chattanooga,
three hours down the road,

00:29:11.620 --> 00:29:13.350
and they hadn't heard of it.

00:29:13.350 --> 00:29:15.270
So we launched the
following effort.

00:29:15.270 --> 00:29:20.370
We chose nine cities and went to
senior leaders in those cities

00:29:20.370 --> 00:29:24.210
and said look, identify
for us 10 young leaders

00:29:24.210 --> 00:29:26.640
who you believe will
help lead the city

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:27.990
in the next generation.

00:29:27.990 --> 00:29:30.570
And they should come from
business and government

00:29:30.570 --> 00:29:32.790
and nonprofits and
educational institutions

00:29:32.790 --> 00:29:35.730
and faith-based organizations,
from anywhere in the community.

00:29:35.730 --> 00:29:37.470
All right, just
bring them to us.

00:29:37.470 --> 00:29:39.960
And nine cities times
10 people, now, we've

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:40.910
got a classroom full.

00:29:40.910 --> 00:29:42.990
All right, so we
bring them to campus

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:45.750
for essentially a
week-long boot camp

00:29:45.750 --> 00:29:48.822
in cross-sector collaboration
for shared prosperity.

00:29:48.822 --> 00:29:50.280
And I want to tell
you, if you want

00:29:50.280 --> 00:29:53.700
to feel optimistic
about America,

00:29:53.700 --> 00:29:57.690
turn off CNN, turn off Fox
News, put down the newspaper,

00:29:57.690 --> 00:30:00.750
and spend a week in a classroom
with these young leaders.

00:30:00.750 --> 00:30:03.570
It's They're truly inspiring,
truly extraordinary the things

00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:04.800
they're doing.

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:06.900
So this brings me, in
fact, to my kind of call

00:30:06.900 --> 00:30:09.240
to action for you.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:12.240
Yeah, I've had the privilege
of having a lot of my students

00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:17.020
either come from Google
or go to Google afterwards

00:30:17.020 --> 00:30:20.530
or to other highly
influential organizations.

00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:23.790
And I think one of the great
pleasures of working at a place

00:30:23.790 --> 00:30:26.910
like Google is you get
to ask yourself every day

00:30:26.910 --> 00:30:28.770
am I changing the world.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:31.290
All right, but I want to
add a question to your list.

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:34.500
And the question is am
I changing my community.

00:30:34.500 --> 00:30:37.380
All right, am I changing my
community in collaboration

00:30:37.380 --> 00:30:40.460
with cross-sector leaders in
other parts of the community?

00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:43.110
Am I working well
to build the commons

00:30:43.110 --> 00:30:47.490
in my community with
leaders in local government,

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:50.010
leaders in nonprofits, leaders
in educational institutions?

00:30:50.010 --> 00:30:54.000
Because I think, ultimately,
that kind of collaboration,

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:55.910
involving businessmen,
involving many others,

00:30:55.910 --> 00:30:59.430
and working at the local
level to build the commons

00:30:59.430 --> 00:31:01.110
and bring back
shared prosperity,

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:04.360
that is the best bet
we have right now.

00:31:04.360 --> 00:31:06.400
So thanks for hearing
me out on this.

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:09.780
Let me open it up for questions,
thoughts, reflections.

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:12.640
I'd love to hear what
you think about this.

00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:15.660
AUDIENCE: Yes, so your call
to action is very well taken.

00:31:15.660 --> 00:31:18.090
You know, we certainly
all have a responsibility.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:20.190
But in studies of
income inequality

00:31:20.190 --> 00:31:22.720
that I've read,
another huge factor,

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:26.040
there's a strong correlation
between the overweening

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:28.690
strength of the
financial sector--

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:32.710
that excess and anomalous
returns to the financial world,

00:31:32.710 --> 00:31:35.400
lower regulations, seems to
be very strongly correlated

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:40.650
with income inequality,
hedge fund billionaires

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:44.600
being taxed less at carried
interest rates, and so on.

00:31:44.600 --> 00:31:47.650
And a lot of those
people are HBS grads.

00:31:47.650 --> 00:31:49.636
So to what extent can I
turn the tables and ask

00:31:49.636 --> 00:31:51.760
is there institutional
responsibility on that side?

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:53.080
JAN RIVKIN: It's a
very fair question.

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:55.650
The easy answer to is there
institutional responsibility

00:31:55.650 --> 00:31:56.250
is yes.

00:31:56.250 --> 00:31:57.330
All right?

00:31:57.330 --> 00:32:00.030
And just to drive
home your point,

00:32:00.030 --> 00:32:03.570
when you look back
at this chart,

00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:06.037
you ask who are these
individuals up here,

00:32:06.037 --> 00:32:08.370
and they are disproportionately
in the financial sector.

00:32:08.370 --> 00:32:12.750
All right, so boy,
it's a great question.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:16.140
I am certain the question
is better than the answer

00:32:16.140 --> 00:32:19.023
I will give it.

00:32:19.023 --> 00:32:22.450
So yes, there is an
institutional responsibility,

00:32:22.450 --> 00:32:25.320
I think, to encourage
our students

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:29.670
to think broadly about
how they create value

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:30.660
before capturing value.

00:32:30.660 --> 00:32:32.670
All right, and in
fact, it goes back

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:35.760
to the very early history
of Harvard Business School.

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:39.360
The first dean, his
statement to the mission

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:43.290
was to educate people to make
a decent profit decently.

00:32:43.290 --> 00:32:45.150
Right?

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:47.280
I think that there
are, in fact, steps

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:50.580
that we and our peer
institutions have made.

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:52.546
You know, we have
a first-year course

00:32:52.546 --> 00:32:53.920
that looks entirely
at leadership

00:32:53.920 --> 00:32:55.860
and corporate
accountability that

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:58.380
asks what are you
responsibilities to all

00:32:58.380 --> 00:32:59.160
your stakeholders.

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:07.020
We've got colleagues, Rebecca
Henderson and George Serafeim,

00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:09.720
teaching a course called
Reimagining Capitalism, which

00:33:09.720 --> 00:33:15.480
asks the question can capitalism
be a source of solutions

00:33:15.480 --> 00:33:17.430
to the world's
thorniest problems.

00:33:17.430 --> 00:33:22.824
They focus on climate change,
inequality, and corruption.

00:33:22.824 --> 00:33:24.990
You know, I think we often
think of businesses being

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:28.560
a cause of those problems.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:30.947
And they ask can
business, in fact,

00:33:30.947 --> 00:33:32.280
be a solution to those problems.

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:35.411
And it's a having
oversubscribed course.

00:33:35.411 --> 00:33:35.910
So

00:33:35.910 --> 00:33:39.840
And I've got literally
dozens of colleagues

00:33:39.840 --> 00:33:42.780
who look at the future
of market capitalism

00:33:42.780 --> 00:33:48.690
and conclude that we've got
to have changes in that.

00:33:48.690 --> 00:33:51.060
Lynn Paine and Joe Bower, in
a recent "Harvard Business

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:56.220
Review" article, basically
came to a creek very similar

00:33:56.220 --> 00:34:00.960
to yours, asking if the focus
on devotion to shareholder value

00:34:00.960 --> 00:34:06.760
alone leads to outcomes in our
society that are unsustainable.

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:09.690
So I think we've got many
folks who are looking

00:34:09.690 --> 00:34:11.400
into how we address these.

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:15.330
I personally would like to
see changes in how we treat,

00:34:15.330 --> 00:34:18.360
for instance, carried interest.

00:34:18.360 --> 00:34:24.630
I also am fairly sober about
the legislative changes there

00:34:24.630 --> 00:34:27.000
that would be required
to pull that off.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.520
Perhaps, you're more optimistic
than I am about that route.

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:30.630
I don't know.

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:31.960
Would you say you are?

00:34:31.960 --> 00:34:32.493
Or--

00:34:32.493 --> 00:34:33.659
AUDIENCE: It's tough to say.

00:34:33.659 --> 00:34:33.870
Right?

00:34:33.870 --> 00:34:35.828
I mean the current plan
doesn't seem conducive.

00:34:35.828 --> 00:34:39.389
But, you know, we have had
more equitable situations

00:34:39.389 --> 00:34:39.980
in the past.

00:34:39.980 --> 00:34:43.287
And so maybe the silver
lining in today's situation,

00:34:43.287 --> 00:34:45.120
if things are perceived
to be broken enough,

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:46.750
that will create
momentum for change.

00:34:46.750 --> 00:34:48.208
JAN RIVKIN: Yeah,
and the last time

00:34:48.208 --> 00:34:51.989
we saw inequality at this level
was right before the Great

00:34:51.989 --> 00:34:52.860
Depression.

00:34:52.860 --> 00:34:55.230
All right, and that
induced, you know,

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:59.340
in a horribly traumatic
way for our society,

00:34:59.340 --> 00:35:01.470
many of the changes
that I suspect you

00:35:01.470 --> 00:35:04.260
would be very supportive of.

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.440
My hope is that do it
this time without a Great

00:35:06.440 --> 00:35:09.710
Depression and a World War.

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:11.510
But I'm also--

00:35:11.510 --> 00:35:13.110
I feel very sober about that.

00:35:13.110 --> 00:35:15.964
And I would look at how
financial regulation,

00:35:15.964 --> 00:35:17.630
regulations affect
the financial sector,

00:35:17.630 --> 00:35:21.360
has gone since the
financial crisis.

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:25.100
And I worry that we've
made very little progress.

00:35:25.100 --> 00:35:28.130
It is why I place my personal
bets at the local level

00:35:28.130 --> 00:35:31.000
where I see, particularly
local politicians,

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.070
it turns out, you know,
that there's just a greater

00:35:34.070 --> 00:35:36.710
degree of accountability
because their trash has

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:39.590
got to be picked up, and the
snow has got to be cleared.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:42.050
And otherwise, there
are consequences

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:46.370
that re very real
and almost immediate.

