00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:11.150
And I kind of know how
that race is likely to end.

00:47:11.150 --> 00:47:12.620
Right?

00:47:12.620 --> 00:47:16.340
And it's deeply,
deeply worrying.

00:47:16.340 --> 00:47:19.460
Other thoughts or questions?

00:47:19.460 --> 00:47:21.480
Yes, please.

00:47:21.480 --> 00:47:23.570
AUDIENCE: So one
of the arguments

00:47:23.570 --> 00:47:25.520
I've heard from
people who tend to be

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:29.180
on the extreme conservative or
liberal side of the spectrum,

00:47:29.180 --> 00:47:30.860
when confronted with
this type of data,

00:47:30.860 --> 00:47:35.060
is that yes, but people
in the lower income

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:39.114
percentile actually don't
have it as bad as they did

00:47:39.114 --> 00:47:40.280
during the Great Depression.

00:47:40.280 --> 00:47:43.670
So it's not really so
bad because of technology

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:46.130
and that that will continue
to make people's lives better

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:46.970
across the board.

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:48.790
And I just wanted to get
your perspective on it.

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:49.665
JAN RIVKIN: Yeah, no.

00:47:49.665 --> 00:47:52.167
I think it's a great question.

00:47:52.167 --> 00:47:53.750
I think there's some
real truth in it.

00:47:53.750 --> 00:47:59.030
And there's also evidence
that points against it.

00:47:59.030 --> 00:48:02.660
The real truth in it is we
have a hard time putting

00:48:02.660 --> 00:48:07.520
into economic terms adjustments
for how better off am I

00:48:07.520 --> 00:48:11.480
because I've got access
to my smartphone.

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:13.190
Right?

00:48:13.190 --> 00:48:17.330
And the economic technology
for accounting for that

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:19.555
is not very good.

00:48:19.555 --> 00:48:20.930
The other evidence
I see, though,

00:48:20.930 --> 00:48:24.870
is if things are so good at that
end of the income distribution,

00:48:24.870 --> 00:48:27.020
why are people so mad.

00:48:27.020 --> 00:48:28.880
Right?

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:29.870
I don't see--

00:48:32.614 --> 00:48:34.530
I don't have a great
answer for that question.

00:48:34.530 --> 00:48:36.410
Right?

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:39.680
So for sure, we should
get better at measuring.

00:48:39.680 --> 00:48:42.260
But I think we also have
to look in the eye--

00:48:42.260 --> 00:48:44.330
the monster that's out there.

00:48:44.330 --> 00:48:48.740
And so, you know,
there's another, I think,

00:48:48.740 --> 00:48:50.610
deeply interesting question.

00:48:50.610 --> 00:48:52.730
Some of my colleagues
work on it.

00:48:52.730 --> 00:48:53.450
I don't.

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:56.950
And that is what are the
determinants of happiness.

00:48:56.950 --> 00:49:01.070
Right Is it actually
absolute or relative wealth?

00:49:01.070 --> 00:49:03.650
And if it's relative
wealth, then, yes, I'm

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:05.420
better off in absolute
terms than people

00:49:05.420 --> 00:49:06.586
during the Great Depression.

00:49:06.586 --> 00:49:09.140
But I'm actually no happier.

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:14.090
So you know, I think it's a deep
question, not one to which I

00:49:14.090 --> 00:49:15.984
have a great answer.

00:49:15.984 --> 00:49:17.150
Other thoughts or questions?

00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:19.404
Eva.

00:49:19.404 --> 00:49:22.390
EVA: Coming from Germany,
I was living in Germany l

00:49:22.390 --> 00:49:24.800
those days, are there
any lessons learned

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:27.540
from different countries, from
different economies that we

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:29.470
[INAUDIBLE] here in the US?

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:32.430
JAN RIVKIN: Yeah, no, I
think there are great lessons

00:49:32.430 --> 00:49:34.120
in both directions.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:36.900
The first thing I'd
say is our focus here--

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:38.850
and I worried about
it for an audience

00:49:38.850 --> 00:49:40.410
as international as Google.

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:41.880
Right?

00:49:41.880 --> 00:49:44.700
The focus here is on the US.

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:46.830
You know, at HBS, we
teach by the case method.

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:49.690
I view the US as, essentially,
the world's largest case study.

00:49:49.690 --> 00:49:50.190
Right?

00:49:50.190 --> 00:49:51.810
And I think many
of the issues we

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:55.050
see here, in different variants,
apply to advanced economies

00:49:55.050 --> 00:49:57.570
around the world.

00:49:57.570 --> 00:50:01.290
I think there are indicators
that the same kinds of problems

00:50:01.290 --> 00:50:02.700
are arising around the world--

00:50:02.700 --> 00:50:05.950
Brexit, actually, the in
Germany just recently.

00:50:05.950 --> 00:50:06.450
Right?

00:50:06.450 --> 00:50:09.590
I mean I think we can
see that showing up

00:50:09.590 --> 00:50:11.640
in the rise of the far right.

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:13.920
Are there lessons from
the rest of the world

00:50:13.920 --> 00:50:15.690
that the US can learn?

00:50:15.690 --> 00:50:20.100
Absolutely, and I think probably
the apprenticeship system

00:50:20.100 --> 00:50:25.140
and the educational
system in northern Europe

00:50:25.140 --> 00:50:29.010
may be the best example.

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:33.270
The US, for very good reasons,
very well-intended reasons,

00:50:33.270 --> 00:50:38.225
got on a kick toward college
for all, right, and, somehow

00:50:38.225 --> 00:50:40.725
or the other, got the impression
out there among individuals

00:50:40.725 --> 00:50:42.630
that a college degree,
a bachelor's degree,

00:50:42.630 --> 00:50:46.770
no matter what it was in,
right, was the path to success.

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:50.760
And other kinds of
blue collar jobs

00:50:50.760 --> 00:50:52.380
just they weren't
knowledge work.

00:50:52.380 --> 00:50:53.351
They weren't worthy.

00:50:53.351 --> 00:50:53.850
Right?

00:50:53.850 --> 00:50:55.320
You couldn't
convince your parents

00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:57.690
this is where you should go.

00:50:57.690 --> 00:50:59.910
I think that's proven just
to be absolutely wrong.

00:50:59.910 --> 00:51:03.300
And in fact, manufacturing
is knowledge work these days.

00:51:03.300 --> 00:51:06.065
And there are great jobs
out there that are unfilled.

00:51:06.065 --> 00:51:07.890
All right?

00:51:07.890 --> 00:51:11.640
And I think Europe has been
much better, much, much better,

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:14.700
at making sure the
idea of the education

00:51:14.700 --> 00:51:17.370
was to get people toward
fulfilling and prosperous

00:51:17.370 --> 00:51:21.090
lives, not necessarily
toward a college degree.

00:51:21.090 --> 00:51:27.870
That said, I understand
deeply, I hope,

00:51:27.870 --> 00:51:29.760
why people are so
focused on this.

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:32.130
I was speaking with an
African-American colleague

00:51:32.130 --> 00:51:32.730
about this.

00:51:32.730 --> 00:51:35.010
And I asked him, why this
college for all thing?

00:51:35.010 --> 00:51:37.500
And he said, basically, look.

00:51:37.500 --> 00:51:40.950
When you say something not
college for all, what you hear

00:51:40.950 --> 00:51:42.270
is not college for all.

00:51:42.270 --> 00:51:44.400
What I hear is
college for people

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:48.630
who look a certain way and
not college for other people.

00:51:48.630 --> 00:51:51.750
So how we create multiple
paths to prosperity,

00:51:51.750 --> 00:51:54.990
as some colleagues at the
Ed School have put it,

00:51:54.990 --> 00:52:00.050
while also creating opportunity
that's fairly broadly spread,

00:52:00.050 --> 00:52:02.550
I think it's something that's
a uniquely American challenge.

00:52:02.550 --> 00:52:06.090
And we've got to take things
like the apprenticeship system

00:52:06.090 --> 00:52:10.890
from Europe and figure out
how we do it in a way that's

00:52:10.890 --> 00:52:13.086
tailored to this country.

00:52:13.086 --> 00:52:14.460
I'll just end with
one last word.

00:52:14.460 --> 00:52:16.590
I genuinely think--

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:19.290
I genuinely think we are at
a crossroads in the country.

00:52:19.290 --> 00:52:20.790
But the good news is there
actually are two paths.

00:52:20.790 --> 00:52:22.081
We're actually at a crossroads.

00:52:22.081 --> 00:52:22.650
Right?

00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:25.380
There's one path, which is
a kind of path toward unity,

00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:27.510
where, for instance,
business leaders understand

00:52:27.510 --> 00:52:30.450
the enlightened
self-interest they have,

00:52:30.450 --> 00:52:32.280
that they invest in the commons.

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:34.230
They work with the
local government.

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:35.980
And we actually build
the commons back up.

00:52:35.980 --> 00:52:37.479
There's another
path, unfortunately,

00:52:37.479 --> 00:52:38.970
which is the path
toward division,

00:52:38.970 --> 00:52:43.500
and so a path where politicians
realize that, given the media

00:52:43.500 --> 00:52:46.110
we've got, dividing
us against one

00:52:46.110 --> 00:52:47.790
another is the path
towards success.

00:52:47.790 --> 00:52:51.060
And business interests pursue
their narrow self-interest.

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:54.210
And we don't address the
issues in the financial sector

00:52:54.210 --> 00:52:56.010
other sectors of our economy.

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:59.187
And we let the
commons deteriorate.

00:52:59.187 --> 00:53:01.020
But I think they're are
generally two paths.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:05.280
And the cool part about it
is we actually get to decide.

00:53:05.280 --> 00:53:07.670
There are forces
of globalization

00:53:07.670 --> 00:53:10.650
or technological change, which
make one path a little rockier

00:53:10.650 --> 00:53:11.730
than the other.

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:13.740
But individually
and collectively,

00:53:13.740 --> 00:53:14.970
we can choose the path.

00:53:14.970 --> 00:53:17.310
And I hope we all
choose the right one.

00:53:17.310 --> 00:53:20.190
Thank you very much for your
thoughts and your questions

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:21.280
and for your time today.

00:53:21.280 --> 00:53:21.780
Thanks.

00:53:21.780 --> 00:53:24.230
[APPLAUSE]

